Correlation between news and FDI inflows

Based on this posting http://www.sthda.com/english/wiki/correlation-test-between-two-variables-in-r

This test shows p-value = 0.004712, which suggests a significant relationship between the number of news articles and the amount of China FDI by year

cor.test(China_FDI_News$china_fdi, China_FDI_News$total_articles, method = "pearson")
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  China_FDI_News$china_fdi and China_FDI_News$total_articles
## t = 3.3149, df = 15, p-value = 0.004712
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.2467146 0.8616089
## sample estimates:
##       cor 
## 0.6502512
ggscatter(China_FDI_News, x = "china_fdi", y = "total_articles", 
          add = "reg.line", conf.int = TRUE, 
          cor.coef = TRUE, cor.method = "pearson",
          xlab = "China FDI in U.S.", ylab = "News articles studied")

Spearman rank correlation coefficient

Spearmans rho statistic is also used to estimate a rank-based measure of association. This test may be used if the data do not come from a bivariate normal distribution.

-1 indicates a strong negative correlation : this means that every time x increases, y decreases (left panel figure) 0 means that there is no association between the two variables (x and y) (middle panel figure) 1 indicates a strong positive correlation : this means that y increases with x (right panel figure)

In this case, the correlation coefficient between FDI and news articles is .76, suggesting a strong correlation.

cor.test(China_FDI_News$china_fdi, China_FDI_News$total_articles, method = "spearman")
## 
##  Spearman's rank correlation rho
## 
## data:  China_FDI_News$china_fdi and China_FDI_News$total_articles
## S = 196, p-value = 0.0006133
## alternative hypothesis: true rho is not equal to 0
## sample estimates:
##       rho 
## 0.7598039
